omen in politics are marginal or even unwelcome. Based on interviews with MPs and party leaders and an analysis of print and television media in the 2000 and 2006 federal elections, Gendered News reveals an unsettling climate that affects the success of women in office and could deter them from running at all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectionszCanada. 0aJournalismxObjectivityzCanada. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aWomen in mass media. 0aWomen political candidateszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Women in Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482625940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826259/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles